plans, in effect, that would
provide less coverage, but would

10:59.533 --> 11:00.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
give them more choices.

11:00.566 --> 11:01.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

11:01.800 --> 11:03.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ROY BLUNT: Give
them more choices.

11:03.300 --> 11:05.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It might also provide some
more up-front coverage.

11:05.400 --> 11:10.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think one of the lessons we
should have learned from what's
happened with the current

11:12.266 --> 11:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plan is that there is insurance
coverage, but there is not
really, many times, access

11:16.200 --> 11:18.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to health care.

11:18.200 --> 11:20.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you have these high
deductibles, there is every --
there is a disincentive to get

11:20.666 --> 11:25.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the policy, because you would
have to pay another -- I think
the average of deductible

11:25.133 --> 11:30.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
policies on the individual
market is $6,000 per individual
before the insurance really

11:31.300 --> 11:35.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
kicked in, and if two of
you got sick, $12,000.

11:35.200 --> 11:39.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Makes it hard to make that
decision, particularly
when you think what
your family needs is the

11:39.766 --> 11:44.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
