14:40.433 --> 14:44.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That doesn't mean you
benefit by being harsh back.

14:44.166 --> 14:49.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think, generally,
the president's tweets
are not helpful to him.

14:51.200 --> 14:54.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the same time, he's figured
out a way to communicate with
people in ways that no other

14:54.600 --> 14:56.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
president has, or he
wouldn't be president.

14:56.800 --> 15:00.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do those
tweets help his agenda
and the Republican agenda?

15:00.566 --> 15:02.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

15:02.066 --> 15:04.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROY BLUNT: They sometimes they
do and they sometimes don't.

15:04.133 --> 15:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there needs to be
a much more significant
filter on those tweets.

15:09.733 --> 15:12.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's OK to have some unspoken
and untweeted thoughts.

15:12.933 --> 15:16.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Senator Roy
Blunt of Missouri, thank you
very much for joining us.

15:16.966 --> 15:17.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

15:17.966 --> 15:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROY BLUNT: Nice to be with you.

15:21.600 --> 15:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to
President Trump's repeated
and unsubstantiated
claim that three to five

15:34.666 --> 15:39.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
million votes were cast
illegally in the 2016 election.

15:39.500 --> 15:44.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He set up a special
commission to investigate,
but one of its first acts
has drawn condemnation

15:45.233 --> 15:46.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from across the country.

15:46.833 --> 15:48.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Hari Sreenivasan
is here with that.

15:48.800 --> 15:53.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yesterday, the
vice chair of that commission
sent a letter to all 50

15:55.466 --> 15:58.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
states asking for voter data
that includes addresses,
party I.D., voter history, and

16:00.366 --> 16:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Social Security information.

16:02.400 --> 16:06.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The commission asked that data
be sent to the White House
by mid-July, but didn't say

16:06.766 --> 16:11.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how it would be used,
other than to examine for
vulnerabilities in the system.

16:12.933 --> 16:14.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We take a closer look
now with Rick Hasen.

16:14.600 --> 16:17.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He is a law professor
at the University of
California, Irvine.

16:17.166 --> 16:19.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He writes the Election Law blog.

16:19.000 --> 16:22.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Rick, the "NewsHour"'s
been reaching out to
states all day long.

16:22.533 --> 16:27.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have got nine definite
no's, 18 that might comply in
whole or in part, and a few

16:27.433 --> 16:29.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
other states that are
still looking at it.

16:29.533 --> 16:33.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Often, what we hear there is
that there are apparently laws
on the books in certain states

16:33.700 --> 16:38.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that prohibit, even if it's
public information, who can look
at the information and why it

16:38.200 --> 16:39.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can be looked at.

16:39.333 --> 16:41.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Explain.

16:41.400 --> 16:43.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK HASEN, University of
California, Irvine: Well, some
of this information, depending

16:43.300 --> 16:45.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on the state, is
available publicly.

16:45.300 --> 16:46.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
People can buy it.

16:46.300 --> 16:48.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Some of this is not available.

16:48.300 --> 16:52.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, just before we
came on, I saw a story that Kris
Kobach himself, the personal

16:54.533 --> 16:56.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
who has asked for this
information, he himself
cannot produce the
Social Security numbers

16:56.833 --> 17:00.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that he has demanded because
that would violate the law
in the state of Kansas.

17:00.600 --> 17:03.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This doesn't seem to have
been very well thought out.

17:03.266 --> 17:07.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Not only do we not know what
the information is going
to be used exactly to do.

17:07.400 --> 17:11.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It doesn't appear that this
information even legally can be
provided by a lot of the states.

17:11.733 --> 17:14.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Kris
Kobach, as his role as secretary
of state of Kansas, can't

17:14.566 --> 17:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
provide the information
that he's asking for, right?

17:16.333 --> 17:17.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICK HASEN: To himself.

17:17.333 --> 17:18.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's right.

17:18.333 --> 17:19.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Got it.

17:19.333 --> 17:20.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right.

17:20.833 --> 17:22.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
All right, what about the
scope of the investigation?

17:22.833 --> 17:26.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There seems to be a lot of
focus on measuring or protecting
the integrity one person, one

17:26.800 --> 17:28.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
vote.

17:28.800 --> 17:31.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't see any description in
here about any Russian meddling
that might have happened.

17:31.133 --> 17:35.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK HASEN: Well, so it's
not clear exactly what this
commission is going to do.

17:35.000 --> 17:39.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Initially, the president said
he wanted to look into the
potential for voter fraud.

17:39.400 --> 17:43.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are a couple of Democrats
on the commission who said that
they wanted to look into Russian

17:43.566 --> 17:45.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
meddling.

17:45.666 --> 17:49.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kobach said he might be open
to that, but that wasn't on
the list of questions that

17:49.166 --> 17:52.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
