state election officials.

17:52.100 --> 17:55.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not clear what this
group is going to do, what
it's going to produce.

17:55.066 --> 17:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I'm concerned that
it's going to be something
that is just going to try
to support the president's

17:59.566 --> 18:03.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
agenda, claiming that there's
a lot of voter fraud, and use
that to make it harder for

18:03.533 --> 18:06.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
people to be able
to register to vote.

18:06.066 --> 18:09.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is this
the kind of information
that a campaign really
would pay money for?

18:09.800 --> 18:14.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK HASEN: Well, in some
states, campaigns do pay money
for this kind of information.

18:16.800 --> 18:20.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The fact that the
information is going to
sent to the president's
office is concerning.

18:22.433 --> 18:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rather than having
outside professional staff
or rather than having
social scientists who

18:25.733 --> 18:30.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
study this information, we know
that this information is going
literally to the executive

18:31.466 --> 18:32.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
office of the president.

18:32.666 --> 18:34.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We don't know how
it's going to be kept.

18:34.300 --> 18:36.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We don't know how secure
it's going to be, on
what kind of servers.

18:36.100 --> 18:38.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We don't have any information.

18:38.133 --> 18:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the concerns about privacy,
about identity theft, about
the information being used for

18:41.433 --> 18:44.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
political purposes, I think
these are all legitimate
questions to be asked.

18:44.766 --> 18:48.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, finally,
is there a question here on the
role of the federal government?

18:48.533 --> 18:51.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There seemed to be some pushback
from states when it came to
the Department of Homeland

18:51.833 --> 18:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Security going out to them,
saying we have this potential
for hacking, we would like

18:55.000 --> 18:56.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to help you secure
your networks.

18:56.466 --> 18:58.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICK HASEN: Absolutely.

18:58.666 --> 19:02.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There has been this long
tradition, especially on
the Republican side, of
talking about federalism

19:02.066 --> 19:04.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and states' rights in this area.

19:04.066 --> 19:07.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we're even seeing some
pushback now from states like
Mississippi that are saying they

19:07.433 --> 19:10.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are not going to cooperate
with providing this information
to the federal government.

19:10.733 --> 19:13.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All
right, Rick Hasen, a
professor at University
of California, Irvine,

19:13.633 --> 19:14.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
thanks so much.

19:14.633 --> 19:19.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICK HASEN: Thank you.

