22:56.800 --> 23:01.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the alliance is important
to the security of both our
countries and the stability of

23:02.400 --> 23:04.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Northeast Asia.

23:04.466 --> 23:08.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The way you framed that
question, that it's
going to lead to the
resolution of the issue

23:08.500 --> 23:13.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with North Korea, is a
bit of a reach from at
least what I could take
away from the meeting.

23:13.100 --> 23:17.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You
and several other former
Cabinet officials and
senators wrote a letter

23:17.266 --> 23:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the Trump administration
where you urged that they take
direct immediate talks with

23:24.100 --> 23:27.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the North Koreans, possibly
send a high-ranking
envoy to North Korea,.

23:27.433 --> 23:29.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Why do you think
that's a good idea?

23:29.266 --> 23:32.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ROBERT GALLUCCI: For
a variety of reasons.

23:32.000 --> 23:36.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that people who favor
negotiations do so partly
because the alternatives are

23:36.800 --> 23:38.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
miserable.

23:38.933 --> 23:42.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There are fundamentally
three options in dealing
with North Korea, and
there always have been

23:42.766 --> 23:45.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
since the end of the Korean War.

23:45.200 --> 23:48.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One is to contain
the North Koreans.

23:48.366 --> 23:50.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we have been doing that,
and we have done it for decades.

23:50.933 --> 23:54.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have been doing that
actually for the eight years
of the Obama administration.

23:54.033 --> 23:58.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I would say that was a
containment or strategic
patience type of policy.

23:58.766 --> 24:03.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The problem with containment is
that it doesn't stop with North
Koreans from developing assets

24:03.500 --> 24:06.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and capabilities and threat that
we would rather they not have.

24:06.966 --> 24:11.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, a second option is to
negotiate and to see whether we
cannot reach an agreement with

24:13.933 --> 24:18.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the North Koreans where they
agree to give up a capability
which we believe they shouldn't

24:18.666 --> 24:21.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
have and is threatening
to friends and allies.

24:21.033 --> 24:25.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is what we attempted
to do in 1994 with
the agreed framework.

24:25.833 --> 24:30.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A third option is to use
military force, something
which we are proud
always to say is on the

24:31.766 --> 24:33.266 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
table, something
we haven't done.

24:33.266 --> 24:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, by that, we do not mean
launching another Korean War.

24:36.533 --> 24:41.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We mean the use of military
force in some limited way
to attack the capability.

24:43.533 --> 24:46.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, it's not only the
nuclear weapons, but it's those
long-range, ICBM-range ballistic

24:46.433 --> 24:48.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
missiles.

24:48.933 --> 24:51.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In your
letter, though, you're
clearly arguing for
point two negotiation.

24:51.033 --> 24:54.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there are some people, as
you well know, in the foreign
policy establishment who say

24:54.833 --> 24:57.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you cannot negotiate
with the North Koreans.

24:57.100 --> 24:59.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I'm just curious
how you respond to that.

24:59.166 --> 25:03.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT GALLUCCI: I think
it's a fair thing to
say that negotiations
with the North Koreans

25:04.633 --> 25:06.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are not guaranteed to succeed.

25:06.666 --> 25:11.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, certainly, through
the years of the Bush
administration, Bush
43, the 2000s, there

25:13.333 --> 25:16.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
were many efforts by
very capable people to
negotiate with the North
Koreans, and it didn't

25:17.233 --> 25:19.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
produce very much.

25:19.633 --> 25:23.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even the agreement
which stuck for eight
years, the agreed framework
I mentioned before,

25:25.300 --> 25:29.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stuck for a while and stopped
the plutonium program from
producing nuclear weapons.

25:29.333 --> 25:31.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Ultimately, it
collapsed as well.

25:31.366 --> 25:36.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there is reason to say that
negotiations with the North
Koreans are not easy, they

25:36.300 --> 25:41.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
may not succeed, but they may
be a way of getting to where
we want to get to, limiting

25:43.333 --> 25:46.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the capability of the North
Koreans to do harm to us and
our allies without the use

25:48.300 --> 25:50.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of military force and
without the risk of a major
war in Northeast Asia.

25:50.433 --> 25:55.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The Chinese
have floated another possible
entreaty to the North Koreans,

25:56.933 --> 26:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that's for the U.S. and
the South Koreans to stop these
annual military exercises.

26:02.066 --> 26:04.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How important is that to
the North Koreans and do you
think that that's a good idea?

26:04.400 --> 26:09.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GALLUCCI: The North
Koreans have said frequently
that they are very unhappy about

26:10.266 --> 26:14.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the U.S.-ROK military exercises.

26:14.833 --> 26:17.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I do believe they
are unhappy about them.

26:17.133 --> 26:20.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You actually
had some recent meetings with
North Korean officials and you

26:20.233 --> 26:22.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
