know, off of insurance.

40:15.366 --> 40:19.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, this is not a
recipe for success.

40:19.800 --> 40:21.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF:
David, that's right.

40:21.866 --> 40:25.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, the president did tweet
this morning, well, if they
can't agree, they should repeal

40:25.200 --> 40:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
now and replace it later.

40:27.033 --> 40:30.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, it's the
definition of bad leadership.

40:30.133 --> 40:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He had a more sensible position
not too long ago, which is
you do both things at the same

40:34.000 --> 40:36.533 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
time.

40:36.533 --> 40:39.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you repeal in the
fantasy that you're going
to replace later, when
you can't replace now,

40:39.466 --> 40:41.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's just not a realistic
way to make policy.

40:41.600 --> 40:44.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think Senator Blunt made
a good point, that, we got
a piece of legislation.

40:44.666 --> 40:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you can't agree on this,
there's not some mythical future
piece of legislation out there

40:48.366 --> 40:50.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's going to pass.

40:50.466 --> 40:54.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The basic problem is
that this is a bill that
massively redistributes
wealth from the poor

40:55.333 --> 40:57.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the rich.

40:57.333 --> 41:01.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there are a lot of senators,
including Bob Corker of
Tennessee and Portman of Ohio

41:03.533 --> 41:06.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Susan Collins of Maine,
who are just uncomfortable
with the level of upward
redistribution that

41:06.100 --> 41:08.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this bill entails.

41:08.200 --> 41:11.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then there are other
senators on the right,
the Ted Cruzes, who
just want to get rid of

41:11.333 --> 41:13.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what they call
job-killing taxes.

41:13.666 --> 41:15.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's just a diverse party.

41:15.700 --> 41:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And McConnell is trying super
hard to find some formula
that will please both sides,

41:20.166 --> 41:22.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but it just may be an
unsolvable problem.

41:22.000 --> 41:24.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: I will
just add one thing, Judy.

41:24.066 --> 41:28.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You had an interview earlier
this week with Senator John
Thune of South Dakota, ranking

41:28.433 --> 41:30.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Republican.

41:30.466 --> 41:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you asked him about one
little mishap, which was that
Dean Heller, the most vulnerable

41:36.400 --> 41:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Republican incumbent in the
country, up in Nevada next
year, in the only state where

41:40.933 --> 41:45.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
