ratings, juiced them up.

47:53.933 --> 47:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I don't understand
where -- if anything,
it's but counterproductive
in every sense.

48:00.933 --> 48:04.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it is true,
David, that this is -- it's
hard to find you said there

48:06.700 --> 48:10.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
may be a silver lining in
fresh outrage, but beyond
that, I'm not sure where it is.

48:10.100 --> 48:11.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: No.

48:11.533 --> 48:14.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, you know, the big question
for me is, do we snapback?

48:14.133 --> 48:18.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do the norms that used to govern
politics reestablish themselves
after the Trump administration,

48:18.833 --> 48:20.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or are we here forever?

48:20.800 --> 48:24.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I hope, from the
level of outrage, that
we have a snap back.

48:24.266 --> 48:26.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But the politics is
broken up and down.

48:26.966 --> 48:31.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Trump may emerge from a
reality TV world that is much
more powerful than we think.

48:33.900 --> 48:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is the prospect
that this is where we are,
which is an horrific thought.

48:35.800 --> 48:36.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Horrific thought.

48:36.800 --> 48:39.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes, it is that.

48:39.066 --> 48:42.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks, we thank you both.

48:42.333 --> 48:47.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Judy.

48:49.266 --> 48:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
Often lost in the health care
debate are the individual

48:59.566 --> 49:04.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stories of fear and
uncertainty that come
with a medical diagnosis.

49:06.600 --> 49:09.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Elizabeth Silver is
an author and attorney
who was unexpectedly
plunged into a world

49:09.533 --> 49:12.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of statistics and probability.

49:12.033 --> 49:15.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She offers her Humble Opinion
on how to consider a prognosis.

49:15.900 --> 49:20.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH SILVER, Author, "The
Tincture of Time": When my
daughter was six weeks old,

49:20.866 --> 49:25.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she suffered a serious stroke
and spent two weeks in the
neonatal intensive care unit.

49:27.833 --> 49:31.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As new parents, my husband
and I spent that time beside
her, waiting for answers and,

49:32.200 --> 49:34.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at the end, were given very few.

49:34.233 --> 49:39.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At home, with a single click,
we could watch videos, read
articles, and, most importantly,

49:41.066 --> 49:44.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stumble across numbers
that would send us either
rejoicing or panicking.

49:44.600 --> 49:48.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Like many parents, we
had nothing to hold
onto but statistics.

49:48.900 --> 49:53.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
According to one I read, her
stroke carried a 20 percent
chance of death and 90 percent

49:55.033 --> 49:57.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
chance of severe
neurological damage.

49:57.066 --> 50:01.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I focused on the 90 percent,
and imagined very different
versions of our lives.

50:01.766 --> 50:06.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the next year, as we
weaved in and out of doctors'
offices, I recalled the aphorism

50:08.333 --> 50:11.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that physicians are
supposed to treat the
patient, not the paper.

50:11.600 --> 50:16.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hippocrates, the ancient Greek
philosopher and physician,
said that it is more important

50:16.300 --> 50:20.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to know what sort of person
has a disease than to know
what sort of disease a person

50:20.766 --> 50:22.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
has.

50:22.466 --> 50:26.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In other words, we must
remember that patients
are people with stories.

50:26.166 --> 50:31.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I took a step back and began
looking at these statistics,
these abstract medical studies

50:33.200 --> 50:37.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and numbers, and started to
view them just as I would
a story, a novel or a film.

50:39.066 --> 50:43.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
After all, a statistic is only
a particular version of a story.

50:43.100 --> 50:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as with all
stories, there are always
multiple perspectives
and multiple truths.

50:50.033 --> 50:53.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can analyze them
like literature: When
was that statistic taken?

50:53.100 --> 50:54.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Who was the source group?

50:54.566 --> 50:56.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Was it self-selecting?

50:56.100 --> 50:59.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What else do the
subjects have in common?

50:59.100 --> 51:04.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When looking at a statistic
in a medical study,
you don't have the full
picture of your prognosis,

51:04.000 --> 51:08.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
unless you have every
perspective, every
detail in the story.

51:08.500 --> 51:13.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that is something you
will never get from a number.

51:15.400 --> 51:18.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Three years later, my daughter
escaped all her damning
statistics and is living a full,

51:19.700 --> 51:22.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
happy life, as if
it never happened.

51:22.233 --> 51:26.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I look closer at her
story in its totality,
those statistics didn't
differentiate based

51:26.666 --> 51:31.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
on age, my prenatal
care, or even the actual
size of the stroke.

51:33.633 --> 51:38.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We all know that statistics
are useful, but if we rely on
them with too much weight, this

51:39.433 --> 51:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can only lead to a breakdown
of trust with medicine.

51:42.000 --> 51:47.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We end up focusing on the 90
percent chance of things going
wrong, and, in the process,

51:48.366 --> 51:51.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
